    <!-- First Paragraph below Main Headline -->
    <p>Boston’s architectural history began in the early 17th century, making it one of the oldest cities in the United States. With over 100 structures listed on the National Register of Historic Places, including the Massachusetts State House and the historic North End featuring colonial-era buildings, Boston showcases its commitment to preserving its architectural legacy. The city is home to nearly 300 designated “Boston Landmarks,” which showcase a diverse range of styles, from the stately Georgian designs to the bold lines of modernist architecture. Each structure serves as a testament to the city’s evolving narrative, inviting residents and visitors alike to explore its layered history.</p>
    
    <p>As the city’s historical backdrop remains a significant draw, Boston’s population surged past 700,000 by the 2020 census, intensifying demand for housing and commercial spaces. This demographic growth has ushered in a wave of modern developments, including ambitious projects like the Millennium Tower and the revitalization of the Seaport District. These modern initiatives reflect the city’s drive for innovation and progress, yet they raise critical concerns about the potential erosion of Boston’s historical character. The juxtaposition of sleek skyscrapers against the backdrop of centuries-old buildings poses questions about identity and heritage, prompting discussions about how best to honor the past while accommodating contemporary needs.</p>

    <p>The challenge of reconciling preservation with development is an ongoing endeavor, and the Boston Zoning Commission plays a crucial role in navigating this complex landscape. Recent initiatives, such as the “Boston 2030” plan, aim to guide sustainable growth while ensuring that historic neighborhoods are not only preserved but also celebrated. This proactive approach emphasizes the importance of integrating new developments with existing architectural treasures, striving for a harmonious coexistence that respects the city’s rich past. It recognizes that the character of Boston is not solely defined by its historic structures, but also by the dynamic interactions between old and new.</p>

    <div class="image-container">
        <img src="building 5.jpg" alt="Historic Neighborhood" >
        <img src="building 6.jpg" alt="Modern Development" >
        <img src="building 7.jpg" alt="Historic Neighborhood" >
